In *Miranda v. Arizona*, 384 U.S. 436 (1966), the Supreme Court held that the Fifth Amendment's protection against self-incrimination requires law enforcement to inform individuals of their rights before conducting a custodial interrogation. The Court established that individuals must be informed of the following rights:

1. The right to remain silent;
2. That anything said can be used against them in a court of law;
3. The right to the presence of an attorney;
4. If they cannot afford an attorney, one will be appointed for them prior to any questioning if they so desire.

These warnings, commonly known as "Miranda rights," are intended to protect individuals from the inherently coercive nature of custodial interrogations. If law enforcement fails to provide these warnings, any statement or confession made by the individual may be deemed inadmissible in court. The decision in *Miranda v. Arizona* thus created a procedural safeguard to ensure that individuals are aware of and can exercise their Fifth Amendment rights during police interrogations.
